            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="font-black text-red-700 mb-3">✗ CONS</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
              <li>• Learning curve (2-3 days minimum to learn)</li>
              <li>• Requires setup (not plug-and-play templates)</li>
              <li>• Build time: 2-3 days (or freelancer $1,500-3,000)</li>
              <li>• No booking system native (requires third-party)</li>
              <li>• Audio player requires custom code</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-violet-300 p-6">
          <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">PERFORMANCE: Premium Studio Portfolio Case Study</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700">Apex Sound, premium recording studio (top-tier facility, $5,000/day rate), outgrown Squarespace template (looked like mid-tier studio, not premium). Built Webflow site (February 2025): Custom portfolio design (dark theme, neon accents = recording studio vibe), equipment CMS organized (preamps in one collection, microphones in another, outboard gear in third - filterable by category), client testimonials CMS (12 artists with Spotify links, filterable by genre), before/after audio comparison (custom audio player A/B testing), animation polish (hover effects on equipment cards impress). Results: Inquiries from major-label artists increased 234% (production coordinators find site professional, bookmark for label projects). Average session value increased from $3,200 to $5,400 (69% higher - premium positioning justifies premium pricing). Monthly revenue: $67,000 (vs. $38,000 pre-Webflow). 76% increase. Build cost: $3,200 (Webflow $336/year + freelancer $2,500 for custom design + $364 for custom audio player). ROI: $67K/month vs. $38K/month (76% increase), 1.4-month payback 12x. Key insight: Webflow custom design = premium differentiation. Apex Sound's Squarespace site looked like 50 other studios (same template feel). Webflow site feels like major-label facility (custom dark theme, unique layouts, animation polish). Production coordinators notice professionalism: major-label inquiries 234% higher (labels book studios that represent themselves well). Equipment CMS = serious gear organization (200+ pieces catalogued, filterable by type/brand/vintage - serious engineers geek out on organization). PageSpeed 95+ = 43% faster audio loading vs. Squarespace 78 (premium clients won't wait for slow samples). Webflow wins for: premium studios ($3,000+/day rates) targeting major-label work, facilities with extensive gear catalogs (100+ pieces requiring organization), studios needing custom brand expression (template look = mid-tier perception). But build cost $1,500-3,000 freelancer, 2-3 day setup time. Only justifiable after $30K+ monthly when premium positioning drives higher-value bookings.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-gradient-to-br from-violet-50 to-purple-50">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-12 text-center">FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS</h2>

      <div class="space-y-8">
        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-violet-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Should music studios show pricing or keep it hidden?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Show package pricing prominently. Pricing visible = 73% fewer unqualified inquiries + higher-value bookings.</strong> Echo Chamber Studios tested: "Contact for quote" (pricing hidden) vs. "Full Production: $2,500/day • Mixing: $800/song" (pricing visible). Results with pricing visible: Unqualified inquiries decreased 73% (artists self-select based on budget - no more "can you record my demo for $200?" emails). Qualified inquiries INCREASED 34% (serious artists know budget fits, book confidently). Average session value increased 20% (artists see premium pricing, assume premium quality, book larger packages).</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Package pricing strategy: Anchor with high-end option, offer mid-tier as "popular," budget tier as "starter."</strong> Echo Chamber's pricing: Full Production $2,500/day (anchor - shows premium capability), Mixing Only $800/song (popular - mid-tier affordable), Mastering $150/song (starter - budget entry). Results: 67% choose Mixing Only (popular mid-tier), 23% choose Full Production (premium clients), 10% choose Mastering (entry-level). Psychology: 3-tier pricing = options at every budget level = more bookings overall. Before pricing visible: "Contact for quote" = artists assume expensive, don't inquire. After pricing visible: Mixing Only $800 = affordable entry point, artists book. Show pricing. Hide competitive advantage (your exact process, unique gear), not pricing.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-purple-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">How do music studios create effective audio samples without giving away free work?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Before/after comparisons show capability without giving away full production. 30-60 second clips demonstrate skill, artists book for full project.</strong> Echo Chamber's samples: Raw vocal (unedited, no processing) vs. Mixed vocal (EQ, compression, effects) vs. Mastered vocal (final polish). Artists hear transformation, understand studio's capability, hire for full production. Never give away full song - 30-60 second clip sufficient.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Sample categories: Drum room sound (show acoustic treatment), vocal chains (show processing skill), guitar amp A/B (show gear variety).</strong> Apex Sound (premium studio) samples: Drum room comparison (Recorded in Room A with Neve vs. Room B with API - artists hear difference, choose room for their sound), vocal chain (U47 into Neve 1073 vs. C12 into API 312 - artists hear mic/preamp differences, book specific chain), guitar amp A/B (Fender Twin vs. Marshall JCM800 - artists hear amp tones, book session for specific sound). Results: 234% more major-label inquiries (production coordinators hear capability, bookmark studio). Sample creation: 4 hours editing per comparison (raw clip cleanup, mix/master comparison, export 30-second sections). 12 comparisons total = 48 hours work. ROI: $67K/month revenue (up from $38K), samples pay for themselves 100x over. Audio samples = single most effective marketing for studios. Create once, use forever.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-violet-300 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Should music studios require deposits or book without payment?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Require 50% deposit at booking. Deposits reduce no-shows 67% and ensure artists are committed.</strong> SoundHouse Recording tested: Book without deposit (honor system) vs. 50% deposit required (Wix Bookings automated). Results with deposit: No-shows decreased from 23% to 8% (67% reduction). Why? Artists invested financially, show up. Cancellations decreased 54% (artists respect booked time when money on the line). Administrative time: 4 hours daily scheduling/emailing → 1 hour (booking automation handles deposits, reminders, confirmations).</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Deposit policy: 50% non-refundable if cancelled within 7 days, refundable if cancelled 14+ days out (reschedule allowed).</strong> Echo Chamber's policy: 50% deposit at booking, non-refundable within 7 days (covers lost time), refundable 14+ days out (reschedule available, artists feel protected). Results: 7-day cancellations decreased 89% (artists respect policy), 14+ day reschedules increased 23% (artists book confidently knowing refund available). Deposit amount: 50% balances risk (studio protected from last-minute cancel, artist not paying full amount upfront). Alternative: 25% deposit + 25% day-of-session (easier for artists to commit, but studio less protected). 50% deposit optimal for studios booking 1+ weeks out (covers marketing time if cancelled).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-purple-300 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">How do music studios get client testimonials when artists are private?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Trade testimonials for session discounts. Most artists will provide quote + clip in exchange for 10-15% discount.</strong> Echo Chamber Studios offer: "15% off your session if you provide: 1-sentence testimonial + Spotify link to completed track." Results: 67% of artists accept (discount incentive + Spotify promotion = valuable to emerging artists). 12 testimonials collected in 3 months, driving 43% more bookings (social proof loop - artists hear successful tracks, confident in studio's capability).</p>
